  "prompt": "My boyfriend cheated on me. I felt betrayed and it still haunts me. How to stop thinking about it?",
  "response": "I'm really sorry that you're going through this. Dealing with betrayal can be incredibly painful and challenging. Here are some steps that might help you work through your feelings and move forward:\n\n1. **Allow Yourself to Grieve:** It's important to acknowledge and process your emotions. Cry if you need to, talk about it with a trusted friend or therapist, and give yourself permission to feel hurt.\n\n2. **Seek Support:** Surround yourself with supportive friends, family, or a therapist who can help you navigate your feelings and provide a safe space to express yourself.\n\n3. **Focus on Self-Care:** Take time to do things that make you feel good and nurture yourself. This could include hobbies, exercise, meditation, or anything that helps you relax and feel happy.\n\n4. **Set Boundaries:** If you feel it's necessary, create boundaries with your ex-boyfriend to limit communication and interactions, giving you space to heal.\n\n5. **Challenge Negative Thoughts:** When you find yourself dwelling on the betrayal, gently challenge those thoughts. Remind yourself of your worth and that you're deserving of love and respect.\n\n6. **Distract Yourself:** Keep yourself busy with activities that you enjoy or that require your full attention. Engaging in new experiences can help shift your focus away from the pain.\n\n7. **Consider Professional Help:** If you find it extremely difficult to move forward, a therapist or counselor can help you process your emotions and develop strategies to cope with the betrayal.\n\n8. **Reflect and Learn:** In time, reflect on the relationship and what you can learn from it. This might help you gain a deeper understanding of what you want and deserve in future relationships.\n\nRemember, healing takes time, and it's okay to take the time you need to recover. You're strong, and you will get through this.",
